://blog.tradehero.mobi/wp-content/uploads/howtochoose.png\" width=\"750\" height=\"250\" /></a>\n\nMany TradeHero users (especially if you\'re new) may ask, <em>I have the application, but I don\'t know how to choose a stock to invest in? How do I go about researching on stocks if no information is given to me? What do the many financial terms in the application mean? I still don\'t know Market Terminology</em>? Fret not, the answers are right here.\n\nWe will be bringing you through a short but succinct series on <strong>How to choose a Stock</strong>. We will also provide you a list of <strong>Market Terminology</strong> that is essential in your trading journey. (Which is actually found on our <a title=\"FAQ\" href=\"http://www.tradehero.mobi/FAQ\" target=\"_blank\">FAQ</a> page!)\n<h2><strong>How to Choose A Stock:</strong></h2>\nWhen choosing a stock, there are several ways people can choose to analyze, and the two most popular methodologies are <strong>Fundamental Analysis</strong> and <strong>Technical Analysis</strong>. This post will be on Fundamental Analysis.\n\nHaving basic knowledge about the stock market will help in investment decisions. Do not worry if you do not understand the many terms and figures that we are about to introduce, it takes more than just theoretical assumptions, it requires a fair amount of application as well! Are you ready?\n<h2>Fundamental Analysis</h2>\nJust what is fundamental analysis? To put it simply, fundamental analysis is gaining knowledge about how a company is doing through a few methods.\n<ul>\n	<li>Traders often use a Macro -&gt; Micro method (or a top-down approach) when using fundamental analysis, and that comprises of the economy, industry and company analysis. To be more specific, traders and investors will narrow down their research to suit the present or future economic environment. This means that using a top-down approach will allow you to have better research results according to what you are looking for!</li>\n</ul>\n<ul>\n	<li>Often enough, stocks are not lone rangers. They tend to move in groups! Factors such asoverall growth rate, market size, and importance to the economy are considered when analyzing industry groups.</li>\n</ul>\n<ul>\n	<li>Financial and annual reports are usually being used as research material when forecasting profits of the company stocks. This will help in getting a basic understanding of the pricing in the stock market.</li>\n</ul>\n&nbsp;\n\nOne key information we feel is pertinent is the knowledge of the \'<strong>true value\' </strong>of a stock.<strong></strong>This encompasses the total value of the company.\n\n<em>\"To find the intrinsic value of a company, investors need to determine the market cap  or establish how much it would cost to buy every single share of company stock at current market prices. This is the total value of the company according to the market  including intangibles, fundamentals, and market conditions. A value stock generally has a market cap which is close to or maybe even lower than the book value.\" - InvestorGuide</em>\n\n<em>\"The market price of a stock tends to move towards its \'intrinsic value\', which is the \'true value\' of a company as calculated by its fundamentals. If the market value does not match the true value of the company, there is an investment opportunity.\" - EuroInvestor</em>\n\nThis means that observing the current market price of a stock and comparing it to the \'true value\' of the company will help in decision making as well. If the market price is below the \'true value\', traders and investors will tend to buy the stocks because it will be expected to rise and move towards its \'true value\'.\n\nWhat factors then determine the \'true value\'? Firstly, you must understand that every investor is different in his or her own ways. There is no rigid structure or formula for a sure-win, but these are some of the valuation factors that are often taken:\n<h2>1. P/E Ratio</h2>\nThe P/E Ratio is defined as the ratio of the company\'s share price to its earnings per share.\n\n<em><strong>P/E Ratio</strong> =Current Share Price / Earnings per Share</em>\n\nThis ratio helps to determine the amount of expectations investors will put in the company\'s shares in the future. The higher the P/E Ratio, the higher the expectations. Sometimes, the P/E ratio is also known as the \'<a href=\"http://wiki.fool.com/P/e_ratio\">Investor Sentiment</a>\'. It also helps to tell if the company\'s share price is undervalued, overvalued or fairly valued. Usually, the displayed P/E Ratio is the Trailing P/E and it takes the four most recent quarters.\n\nFor instance, if a company attains $0.43, $0.66, $0.31 and $0.24 in EPS and the stock price was $15.63, then the P/E ratio would be $15.63/$1.64 = 9.53.\n<h2>2. Return on Equity (ROE)</h2>\nROE is expressed as a percentage, and it helps corporations in calculating their profits by measuring the amount of profit the company earns from the amount the shareholders invest.\n\n<em><strong>ROE</strong> = Net Income/ Shareholder\'s Equity</em>\n\nCompanies with higher growth will be expected to have a higher ROE.\n<h2>3. Profit Margins</h2>\nProfit Margins define as the \'percentage of revenue that a company keeps as profit after accounting for fixed and variable costs.\' To put it in simpler terms, it can be used to represent profit that the company earns per dollar of revenue. This is usually utilized for internal use among industries as the margins vary across different industries.\n\n<em><strong>Profit Margin</strong> = Net Income / Revenue</em>\n<h2>4. Earnings Per Share (EPS)</h2>\nEPS represents the portion of the company\'s profit allocated to one share stock.\n\n<i>EPS= Net income  Total number of capital stock shares</i>\n\nThis is important to investors as it provides them a gauge of how their stock share investments are performing in the stock market, and the amount of business earned. Especially for traders dealing with public trading,they want information such as the net income provided on a per share basis so that they can easily compare it with the market price of their stock shares.\n\n<i></i>\n\nFor more information and to find out the strengths and weaknesses of Fundamental Analysis, we recommend that you visit the following websites:\n\n<address><em></em><a href=\"http://stockcharts.com/school/doku.php?id=chart_school:overview:fundamental_analysis\">Stock Charts</a></address><address>Euorhttp://www.euroinvestor.com/ei-news/2012/02/12/stock-school-5-important-elements-in-fundamental-analysis/15694</address>Stay tuned for the next post on <strong>Technical Analysis</strong>!\n\n&nbsp;\n\n&nbsp;\n\n<address>Resources:</address><address>http://accountingexplained.com/financial/ratios/pe-ratio</address><address>http://wiki.fool.com/P/e_ratio</address><address>http://www.investorguide.com/article/12293/stock-strategies-basics-of-the-value-investing-stock-strategy-igu/</address><address>http://www.investopedia.com/terms/r/returnonequity.asp</address><address>http://ycharts.com/glossary/terms/profit_margin</address><address><address>http://stockcharts.com/school/doku.php?id=chart_school:overview:fundamental_analysis</address><address>http://www.euroinvestor.com/ei-news/2012/02/12/stock-school-5-important-elements-in-fundamental-analysis/15694</address></address>','How to Choose A Stock: Fundamental Analysis','','inherit','closed','open','','295-revision-16','','','2013-06-28 16:53:49','2013-06-28 08:53:49','',295,'http://blog.tradehero.mobi/295-revision-16',0,'revision','',0),(345,4,'2013-06-28 16:54:10','2013-06-28 08:54:10','<a href=\"http://blog.tradehero.mobi/wp-content/uploads/howtochoose.png\"><img class=\"alignnone size-full wp-image-343\" alt=\"howtochoose\" src=\"http://blog.tradehero.mobi/wp-content/uploads/howtochoose.png\" width=\"750\" height=\"250\" /></a>\r\n\r\nMany TradeHero users (especially if you\'re new) may ask, <em>I have the application, but I don\'t know how 